<TEXT>
 President Clinton has urged Russian President Vladimir Putin to order the
 release on humanitarian grounds of a US businessman convicted of spying. A
 White House spokesman says the two leaders spoke by telephone <TIMEX2 val="2000-12-08" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">today</TIMEX2>, after
 the Russian government's pardon commission recommended the release of Edmund
 Pope. Earlier, a senior Russian official said Edmund Pope could be home by
 <TIMEX2 val="" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">Christmas</TIMEX2>. The <TIMEX2 val="PAST_REF" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="2000-12-08T20:03:52.69" anchor_dir="BEFORE" comment="">former</TIMEX2> US naval intelligence officer was convicted and
 sentenced to <TIMEX2 val="P20Y" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">20 years in prison</TIMEX2> <TIMEX2 val="2000-12-13" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">Wednesday</TIMEX2>, on charges he illegally obtained
 a classified information on a Russian torpedo.
</TEXT>
